The paper deals with game theory and network analysis, which are both central topics in computer science. Specifically, the paper focuses on a Hotelling game, which is a classic game theory model used to analyze competition between firms in a market. This suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper considers the distribution of potential customers on a network, which is a topic that falls under the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. The paper also discusses the comparison of equilibrium costs with the optimal cost, which could be relevant to the cs.MA (Multi-Agent Systems) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper analyzes the behavior of a large number of retailers, which could be relevant to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the efficiency of equilibria, which is a topic that falls under the cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) sub-category.
